content.text:
The type errors come from how we’re calling `Effect.catchTags`. In its data-last form (`app.pipe(Effect.catchTags({...}))`) TypeScript has to infer the handled error union *before* it ever sees `app`. With nothing to go on it widens the error type to `unknown`, so the success type coming back from `catchTags` is inferred as

```
HttpServerResponse | {
  [K in keyof Cases]:
    Cases[K] extends (...args) => Effect<infer A, any, any> ? A : never
}[keyof Cases]   // ← collapses to `unknown`
```

That “`… | unknown`” means the result is no longer an `App.Default`, and `HttpMiddleware.make` rejects it. The same inference failure is what triggers the second diagnostic about the `cases` object itself.

Two easy ways to unblock it:

1. Switch to the data‑first overload so the effect is provided before the cases map:

```ts
export const jsonErrorMiddleware = HttpMiddleware.make((app) =>
  Effect.catchTags(app, {
    RepositoryError: () =>
      HttpServerResponse.json({ error: 'storage_failure', detail: 'Unable to persist or fetch records' }, { status: 500 }),
    GithubClientRequestError: () =>
      HttpServerResponse.json({ error: 'github_request_failed', detail: 'Unable to reach GitHub' }, { status: 502 }),
    GithubClientResponseError: (error) =>
      HttpServerResponse.json({ error: 'github_response_failed', detail: `GitHub responded with status ${error.status}` }, { status: 502 }),
    ParseError: parseErrorResponse,
  })
);
```

2. Keep the data-last style but pin the error union explicitly, e.g.

```ts
const withErrorHandlers = Effect.catchTags<
  RepositoryError | GithubClientRequestError | GithubClientResponseError | ParseResult.ParseError
>({
  …
});

export const jsonErrorMiddleware = HttpMiddleware.make((app) => app.pipe(withErrorHandlers));
```

Either approach gives `catchTags` the concrete `_tag` union up front, so it narrows each handler correctly and the result stays an `App.Default`.

